    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Related: #18583, #39723\n\n## Problem\n\n`vim.fs.dir()` currently drops filesystem errors from `uv.fs_scandir()`. If a directory cannot be read, callers see the same result as an empty directory.\n\nThis makes `vim.fs.find()` ambiguous: \"no match exists\" and \"part of the tree could not be searched\" are indistinguishable. If you want this you have to bypass `vim.fs.dir()` via `vim.uv.fs_scandir()` directly.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\n***NOTE***: the following behavior is just a preliminary idea. Perhaps a large refactor to the behavior of these functions on error is in order. The below solution allows `vim.fs.{dir,find}()` to implicitly handle errors silently - in other words, it remains backwards compatible.\n\nAdd an opt-in error callback to `vim.fs.dir()` to be used as follows:\n\n```lua\nfor name, type in vim.fs.dir(path, {\n  depth = math.huge,\n  on_error = function(err, path, errname)\n    -- err: uv error string\n    -- path: directory being scanned\n    -- errname: e.g. \"EACCES\"\n  end,\n}) do\n  ...\nend\n```\n\n- `on_error` is called when the initial uv.fs_scandir(path) fails\n- Recursively, `on_error` is called when any child directory cannot be scanned\n- `vim.fs.find()` forward the same option to `vim.fs.dir()`.\n\nLastly, empty dir behavior != empty, unreadable dir, as in both cases an empty table is returned but only in the latter is `on_error()` fired.",
    "closed_at": null,
